DOCS_modelChunk = [{"ty":"is","ibi":1,"s":"FAQ: We will update this document with new information as it becomes available. 

Q: Will school closings, as directed by the Illinois governor and school board, be made up?

A: No. This will be considered Act of God (AOG) days and will not be required to be made up, nor will they change our established school calendar.


Q: Will the AOG days during the school closure impact spring break or graduation?

A: No, because at this time, those events do not fall within the AOG closure. 


Q: Will the school year be extended into the summer required due to the CoVID 19?

No - all of our Act of God days and Remote Learning Days will count as student attendance days for the purpose of the school calendar. The school year will NOT be extended.


Q: Will credit recovery still be required in the summer?

A: Yes, students may still be required to complete credit recovery, if needed. 


Q: Will the AOG closure impact state assessments like the Illinois Assessment of Readiness, the Illinois Science Assessment, and the PSAT/SAT?

A: Yes. Currently, the PSAT/SAT date of April 14th falls outside the AOG closure and we will test as planned. The IAR and ISA may adjust their testing windows and as soon as we know when the new dates are, we will communicate new information with families.


Q: Will this impact our students scheduled in Driver’s Education, especially those that will require a certain number of hours with an instructor behind-the-wheel?

A: Yes. We are waiting for additional guidance from ISBE, but students may not drive with an instructor during AOG days. Please look for updated information in the near future.


Q: Will my child be accountable for work assigned during the AOG closure?

A: No, not officially. However, we do encourage our families to utilize resources shared by our instructors and published on our website or social media in order to establish a continuity of learning. No new material will be introduced, but reinforcing current academic expectations will ensure a smooth transition when we return to school. 

Q: Can students participate in sports or other extracurricular activities?

A: No. The entire district is closed during AOG days.


Q: How long will schools be closed?
A: At this time we are still planning to open on April 14th. However, this situation is constantly evolving and we do promise to keep families informed as we learn more.

Q: Who should seek medical evaluation for coronavirus?

A: If you have symptoms like cough, fever, or other respiratory problems, contact your regular doctor first. Do not go to the emergency room. Emergency rooms need to be able to serve those with the most critical needs.
If you have difficulty breathing, it doesn’t mean you have novel coronavirus, but you should call 9-1-1.
If you are over 60 and you have underlying conditions like diabetes, heart disease, and lung disease, come up with a plan with your doctor to identify your health risks for coronavirus and how to manage symptoms. Contact your doctor right away if you do have symptoms.

Q: When schools reopen, when should I keep my child home from school?

A: If children are vomiting or have a fever (100 degrees Fahrenheit or greater), they will be sent home and parents will be advised to keep sick children home for at least 24 hours after they stop vomiting or do not show signs of fever without using fever-reducing drugs (any medicine that contains ibuprofen or acetaminophen).

Q: Do you have resources I can use to talk about the coronavirus with my child?

A: As adults, it’s important we remain calm with our actions and words, and share factual information. Sharing accurate information during a time of heightened concern is critical. One of the ways we can protect our community from illness is to keep rumors and misinformation from spreading.
Here are some resources you may use to talk about the coronavirus with children:
